{"title_page": "Culture of London", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2009}}\n[[File:London Big Ben Phone box.jpg|thumb|right|Three cultural icons of London: a [[red telephone box|K2 red telephone box]], [[Big Ben]] and a red [[double-decker bus]]]]\nThe '''culture of London''' concerns the engineering, music, museums, festivals and Asa wholes like you are make[[London]], the capital city of the United Kingdom. London is widely believed to be the culture capital of the world, although this title is disputed with a number of other cities internationally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23389580-london-is-the-world-capital-of-the-21st-century-says-new-york.do |title=Archived copy |accessdate=3 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125224024/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23389580-london-is-the-world-capital-of-the-21st-century-says-new-york.do |archivedate=25 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/london-capital-of-the-world-766661.html | work=The Independent | first=Simon | last=Calder | date=22 December 2007 | location=London | title=London, capital of the world}}</ref> The city is particularly renowned for its theatre quarter, and its [[West End of London|West End]] theatre district has given the name to \"West End theatre\", the strand of mainstream professional theatre staged in the large theatres in London. London is also home to notable cultural attractions such as the [[British Museum]], the [[Tate|Tate Galleries]], the [[National Gallery]], the [[Notting Hill Carnival]] and [[The O2 (London)|The O2]].\n\nThrough music, comedy and theatre, London has a lively nightlife with approximately 25.6 events per thousand people, 44.1% of those events being theatre based.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chadha|first1=Aayush|title=UK Event Data - In Review|url=https://www.tickx.co.uk/article/772|website=www.tickx.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nA variety of landmarks and objects are [[cultural icon]]s associated with London, such as [[Big Ben]], [[Buckingham Palace]] and the [[tube map]]. Many other British cultural icons are strongly associated with London in the minds of visiting tourists, including the [[red telephone box]], the [[AEC Routemaster]] bus, the [[Hackney carriage|black taxi]] and the [[Union Flag]].\n\nThe city is home to many nationalities and the diversity of cultures have shaped the city's culture over time.\n\n==Classical music and opera==\n[[Image:Royal Opera House - Floral Hall - Bow Street - London - 240404.jpg|thumb|left|The Floral Hall of the [[Royal Opera House]]]]\n\nThere are three major concert halls in the capital. One of these is the Barbican Hall at [[Barbican Centre]]; which is home to the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] (LSO) and [[BBC Symphony Orchestra]]. The [[Royal Festival Hall]], based at the [[South Bank|South Bank Centre]] along with the [[Queen Elizabeth Hall]] and the [[Hayward Gallery]] is home to the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]] (LPO), and the [[Philharmonia]]. The final and largest of all venues is the [[Royal Albert Hall]], which hosts the [[Proms]] each summer. The [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] (RPO) is also based in London at [[Cadogan Hall]].\n\nThere are also several chamber orchestras, some of which specialise in period instrument performances, including the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]], and the [[Academy of St Martin-in-the-Fields|Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields]]. Chamber music venues include the [[Purcell Room]] at the [[South Bank|South Bank Centre]]; the [[Wigmore Hall]] and [[St. John's, Smith Square|St John's, Smith Square]].\n\nA number of [[:Category:London choirs|choirs]] have originated in London, varying in size and musical style. Among the city's large symphonic concert choirs are the [[London Philharmonic Choir]] and [[London Symphony Chorus]], which have their origins as the choral sections of the LPO and the LSO,<ref name=lsc>{{cite web|title=About the LSC|url=http://www.lsc.org.uk/about|publisher=London Symphony Chorus|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=lpo>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.lpc.org.uk/60/history.html|publisher=London Philharmonic Choir|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> the [[London Chorus]], [[London Voices]] and [[the Bach Choir]]. Smaller vocal groups in London include the [[Holst Singers]]<ref>{{cite web|title=About us|url=http://holstsingers.co.uk/about-us/the-choir/|publisher=Holst Singers|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> and the choir of [[the English Concert]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Choir of The English Concert|url=http://www.englishconcert.co.uk/biographies/detail.php?ID=1837|publisher=The English Concert|accessdate=10 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018041745/http://www.englishconcert.co.uk/biographies/detail.php?ID=1837|archivedate=18 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There is also a long tradition of choral singing in Christian churches and cathedrals, and among the choirs associated with [[List of churches in London|London churches]] are the choirs of [[St Paul's Cathedral]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Choir & Musicians|url=http://www.stpauls.co.uk/Worship-Music/Choir-Musicians|publisher=St Paul's Cathedra|accessdate=10 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811111254/http://www.stpauls.co.uk/Worship-Music/Choir-Musicians|archive-date=11 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Choir of Westminster Abbey|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/music/choir|publisher=Westminster Abbey|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> and [[Westminster Cathedral]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Westminster Cathedral Choir|url=http://www.westminstercathedral.org.uk/music_choir.php|publisher=Westminster Cathedral|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> which sing daily services.\n\nThe [[Royal Opera House]] at [[Covent Garden]] is home to the Royal Opera and [[Royal Ballet, London|Royal Ballet]] companies. The other main opera company is the [[English National Opera]]. In the summer opera is performed in a temporary pavilion by [[Opera Holland Park]], and there are occasional performances by visiting opera companies and small freelance professional opera companies.\n\n==Popular music==\n[[File:AmyWinehouseBerlin2007.jpg|thumb|[[Amy Winehouse]] was a singer-songwriter from Southgate, north London.]]\nLondon is famous for its rock scene, and was the starting point of some of the greatest 60s and 70s artists such as [[David Bowie]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[The Clash]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[The Sex Pistols]], [[The Who]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and popular 90s acts like [[blur (band)|Blur]] and [[Coldplay]].  Most major bands' tours will pass through London as well, favourite venues being the [[Brixton Academy]], the [[The O2 Arena|O2 Arena]], and the [[Hammersmith Apollo]].\n\nIn addition to spawning the bands mentioned above, London, in its capacity as the UK's cultural centre, has served as the base of a number of internationally important acts, including [[The Beatles]] and [[Elton John]], as well as being instrumental in the birth of [[Electronic dance music|dance music]].\n\nLondon is also known for spawning numerous massively successful pop acts; with the [[Spice Girls]], [[Cliff Richard]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[One Direction]] and [[Little Mix]]   being especially noteworthy.\n\nLondon also has a thriving urban scene, mainly throughout the 21st century. Soul singers like [[Adele]], [[Amy Winehouse]] and [[Lemar]] have found themselves chart, and international success.  [[R&B]] singers such as the [[Sugababes]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Taio Cruz]], [[Jay Sean]] and [[Alexandra Burke]] are also extremely popular. London also has a strong rap scene; rappers including [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]] and [[Dizzee Rascal]] among others have helped contribute to London gaining the status of having the strongest rap scene outside of the USA.\n\nLondon is the home of one of the biggest underground scenes in the world. Genres include [[Uk garage]], [[Drum and bass]], [[Dubstep]], [[2-step garage|2step]] and [[Grime (music)|grime]].\n\n==Festivals==\n[[Image:London - Notting Hill Carnival - Girl in Costume.jpg|thumb|right|Girl in costume at the [[Notting Hill Carnival]]]]\nLondon hosts several festivals, fairs and carnivals throughout the year with over 40 free festivals each year. The most famous is the [[Notting Hill Carnival]], the world's second largest carnival. The carnival takes place over the August bank holiday weekend, and attracts almost 1 million people. It has a distinctly Afro-Caribbean flavour, and highlights include a competition between London's [[steelpan]] bands and a 3-mile street parade with dancing and music.\n\nLondon also hosts the [[Carnaval Del Pueblo]], Europe's greatest Latin American Festival, held on the first Sunday of August each year. Seven countries participate in this street procession, which ends in Burgess Park. Live music, dance, and Funfairs go up to 9:30&nbsp;pm.\n\nThere are also large parades held on [[St. George's Day]] (23 April) and [[St Patrick's Day]] (17 March).  The [[Dance Umbrella]] is held every October, and features a variety of dance companies putting on displays across London.  In addition there are many smaller fairs and parades, including the [[Christmas Without Cruelty Fayre]], a fair held annually to promote [[animal rights]].\n\n[[File:Palace Theatre London.jpg|thumb|left|[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]] at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]]]]\n==Theatre and dance==\nThere are over three dozen major theatres, most concentrated in the [[West End of London|West End]] (see the articles West End theatre and [[List of London venues]]). West End theatres are commercial ventures that host predominantly Musical Theatre shows but genres such as comedy and serious drama are sometimes shown. The subsidised or non-commercial theatre is vibrant in the capital with theatres like the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] and [[Shakespeare's Globe]] both of which are based on the [[South Bank]], the [[Barbican Centre|Barbican]] in the city, the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]] which specialises in new drama, and the [[Old Vic]]; and [[Young Vic]], both in [[Lambeth]]. The [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] which is based in [[Stratford-upon-Avon|Stratford]], presents seasons in London as well. Smaller fringe theatres like [[Battersea Arts Centre]], [[Bloomsbury Theatre]], [[Almeida Theatre]] and [[Tricycle Theatre]] are also popular.\n\nThe capital also boasts a successful dance and physical theatre scene, home to two ballet companies; the [[Royal Ballet]] based at the [[Royal Opera House]] and [[English National Ballet]] based in [[Kensington]], performing at the [[London Coliseum]]. [[Sadler's Wells Theatre]] on Rosebery Avenue in [[Islington]] exclusively shows dance performances throughout the year ranging from existing and new [[Contemporary Dance|Contemporary]] companies, Musical Theatre, and touring ballet companies. Dance performances also take place at the [[Barbican Centre]], [[Peacock Theatre]] (Sadler's Wells), and the [[Queen Elizabeth Hall]]. [[Rambert Dance Company|Rambert]], [[Richard Alston Dance Company]], [[Candoco]], and [[Siobhan Davies Dance]] are all based in London as well as choreographers such as [[Matthew Bourne]], [[Wayne McGregor]], [[Lloyd Newson]], and [[Hofesh Shechter]] also basing their companies within the capital.\n\n==Art==\n[[Image:National Gallery head-on shot.jpg|thumb|[[National Gallery (London)|The National Gallery]] from Trafalgar Square]]\nThe British National collection of Western Art to 1900 is held at [[National Gallery, London|The National Gallery]]. Other major collections of pre-1900 art are The [[Wallace Collection]]; the Courtauld Gallery at the [[Courtauld Institute of Art]]; and [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]]. The national collection of post-1900 art is at [[Tate Modern]] and the national collection of British Art is at [[Tate Britain]]. [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|The National Portrait Gallery]] has a major collection dedicated to prominent British people from all periods. The [[Royal Academy]]'s temporary exhibitions are also important.\n\nIn addition to [[Tate Modern]] major contemporary art venues include [[White Cube]], the [[Saatchi Gallery]], and The [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA]].\n\n==Museums and art galleries==\n\n[[Image:British museum facade (1).jpg|thumb|The main entrance to the [[British Museum]]]]\n{{main|List of London museums}}\n\nLondon is home to over 240 museums,<ref>{{cite web|title=Culture of London|url=http://europe-cities.com/destinations/uk_england/cities/london/culture/|website=Europe-Cities|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> galleries, and other institutions, many of which are free of admission charges and are major [[tourist attraction]]s as well as playing a research role. The first of these to be established was the [[British Museum]] in [[Bloomsbury]], in 1753. Originally containing antiquities, natural history specimens and the national library, the museum now has 7 million artefacts from around the globe. Also of eighteenth-century foundation is the [[Royal Academy|Royal Academy of Arts]]; its [[Royal Academy summer exhibition|summer exhibition]] has been an annual fixture on the London social calendar since 1769. In 1824 the [[National Gallery]] was founded to house the British national collection of Western paintings; this now occupies a prominent position in [[Trafalgar Square]].\n\nIn the latter half of the nineteenth century the locale of [[South Kensington]] was developed as \"[[Albertopolis]]\", a cultural and scientific quarter. Three major national museums are located there: the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] (for the [[applied arts|applied]] and [[Decorative arts]]), the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] and the [[London Science Museum|Science Museum]]. The national gallery of British art is at [[Tate Britain]], originally established as an annexe of the National Gallery in 1897. The Tate Gallery, as it was formerly known, also became a major centre for modern art; in 2000 this collection moved to [[Tate Modern]], a new gallery housed in the former [[Bankside Power Station]]. London's museums of military and maritime history also opened in the twentieth century: the [[Imperial War Museum]] in 1917, and the [[National Maritime Museum]] in 1934.\n\nLondon has several smaller museums of note. The [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]] was the first purpose-built public art gallery in England, opening in 1817. Its architect, Sir [[John Soane]], turned his own house in [[Lincoln's Inn Fields]] into a museum and architectural showcase, known as the [[Sir John Soane's Museum|Soane Museum]]. The [[Wallace Collection]] is a notable small collection of [[Old Master]] paintings and furniture, with an emphasis on French works. The [[Courtauld Institute of Art]], which pioneered the study of [[art history]] in Britain from its foundation in 1932, is now located in [[Somerset House]], the former premises of the Royal Academy. The [[Museum of London]], charting the capital's history, has been located in the [[Barbican Centre|Barbican]] complex since 1976; a [[Museum of London Docklands|sister museum in the Docklands]] opened in 2003.\n\n==Libraries==\n[[File:Maughan-library-1.jpg|thumb|[[Maughan Library]], [[King's College London]]]]\n\nThe [[British Library]], located on [[Euston Road]] in [[St Pancras, London|St Pancras]] is the [[List of largest libraries|largest library in the world]]. It is the [[national library]] of the United Kingdom and is a [[legal deposit library]].<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/british-library|publisher=HM Government|title=British Library|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2003/28/pdfs/ukpga_20030028_en.pdf|publisher=HM Government|website=Legislation|title=Legal Deposit Libraries Act 2003|pages=2-3}}</ref> There are many local public libraries across London, with each borough having its own library system, joined through the London Libraries network.<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/our-key-themes/culture-sport-and-tourism/arts-and-culture/networks/association-london-chief|title=London Libraries|publisher=London Councils|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref> Some notable local libraries include [[Kensington Central Library]] and the [[Barbican Library]]. There are also private subscription libraries, including the [[London Library]].<ref>{{cite-news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/31732a86-6753-11e9-9adc-98bf1d35a056|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=3 Jan 2020|date=26 April 2019|title=Shhh! Private libraries are making a quiet comeback}}</ref>\n\nThere are many research libraries in London, including the [[Wellcome Library]] and [[Dana Library and Research Centre|Dana Centre]].<ref>{{cite-news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/futurelondon/culturecity/best-libraries-in-london-wellcome-trust-british-library-canada-water-victoria-and-albert-guildhall-a4072696.html|title=Best libraries in London|publisher=[[Evening Standard]]|access-date=3 January 2020|date=21 Feb 2019}}</ref> There are also many [[academic library|university libraries]], including the [[British Library of Political and Economic Science]] at [[London School of Economics|LSE]], the [[Imperial College Central Library|Central Library]] at [[Imperial College London|Imperial]], the [[Maughan Library]] at [[King's College London|King's]], and the [[Senate House Libraries]] at the [[University of London]]. Many learned institutions host a library such as the [[Inner Temple Library]], and the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]] contains the [[House of Commons Library]] and the [[House of Lords Library]].<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://aim25.com/which_inst.htm|title=List of repositories|access-date=3 Jan 2020|publisher=Archives in London and the M25 area}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/commons-library|title=House of Commons Library|publisher=UK Parliament|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/lords/work-of-the-house-of-lords/lords-library/|title=The House of Lords Library|publisher=UK Parliament|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Night-life==\n[[Image:BrixtonAcademy.jpg|thumb|[[Brixton Academy]]]]\nApart from the pubs and clubs, there are many music venues. Among the best known are [[Shepherds Bush Empire]], [[Brixton Academy]], [[Hammersmith Apollo]], [[Wembley Arena]], [[The Marquee]], [[The UCL Bloomsbury]], the [[Royal Albert Hall]] and the [[London Astoria]], which has now closed.<ref>http://www.festivalrepublic.com/venues/#Astoria {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220070927/http://www.festivalrepublic.com/venues/ |date=20 December 2007 }}</ref> Between 2007 and 2015, London lost 35% of its grassroots music venues, threatening the city's role as an incubator of new musical talent.<ref>https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/rescue_plan_for_londons_grassroots_music_venues_-_progress_update_-_jan_2017.pdf</ref> London is home to many clubs such as the [[Ministry of Sound]].\n\n\nThere are many other culture related attractions in London, including the [[Avenue of Stars, London|Avenue of Stars]], a walkway similar to the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], with stars commemorating notable individuals or groups.\n\nLondon also has a thriving LGBT community with a high number of venues catering to gays and lesbians, such as [[G-A-Y]], [[The Black Cap]], [[Coleherne public house|The Coleherne]] and [[Heaven (nightclub)|Heaven]]. However, London lost 58% of its [[LGBT]]Q+ night time venues between 2006 and 2017.<ref>https://www.ucl.ac.uk/urbanlab/docs/executive-summary-lgbtq-cultural-infrastructure-in-london-night-venues</ref> Spaces catering to [[Black and Minority Ethnic|BAME]] [[LGBT]]Q+ people have been disproportionately vulnerable to closure.\n\nComedy is widely popular with the capital having around 100 venues showing '[[Alternative Comedy]].' London is also home to [[The Comedy Store (London)|The Comedy Store]] one of the longest running comedy venues in the world.\n\n==Sport==\n{{main|Sport in London}}\n\nLondon is the home of many professional sport teams and has hosted various international sporting events, including the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer Olympics]] in [[1908 Summer Olympics|1908]], [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948]], and [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012]]. [[Association football|Football]] is very popular and London is home to [[Wembley Stadium]] as well as club stadiums such as the [[Emirates Stadium]], [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]. [[Cricket]] grounds such as [[Lord's]] and [[The Oval]] are in London and [[rugby league]] and [[rugby union]] are popular team sports in the city. [[The Boat Race]] and [[The Championships, Wimbledon|The Wimbledon Championships]], among the most famous contests in rowing and tennis, respectively, occur in London. The [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] hosts athletics events.\n\n== Culture Tourism ==\nCultural tourism is growing as London became the second most visited city in the world in 2017,{{cn|date=January 2020}} and many travellers come here to enjoy the British way of living. Culture tourism generates \u00a33.2 billion per year for London's economy and supports around 80,000 jobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/take_a_closer_look-_a_cultural_tourism_vision_for_london_2015_-_2017.pdf|title=A CULTURAL TOURISM VISION FOR LONDON 2015 \u2013 2017|website=www.london.gov.uk}}</ref> This is the reason why London is now being promoted as a cultural centre to attract more and more tourists and compete with places like Amsterdam, Paris and New York which are known for their authentic culture.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Culture by city in England|London]]\n[[Category:Culture in London| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2009}}\n[[File:London Big Ben Phone box.jpg|thumb|right|Three cultural icons of London: a [[red telephone box|K2 red telephone box]], [[Big Ben]] and a red [[double-decker bus]]]]\nThe '''culture of London''' concerns the engineering, music, museums, festivals and others. [[London]], the capital city of the United Kingdom. London is widely believed to be the culture capital of the world, although this title is disputed with a number of other cities internationally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23389580-london-is-the-world-capital-of-the-21st-century-says-new-york.do |title=Archived copy |accessdate=3 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125224024/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/news/article-23389580-london-is-the-world-capital-of-the-21st-century-says-new-york.do |archivedate=25 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/news-and-advice/london-capital-of-the-world-766661.html | work=The Independent | first=Simon | last=Calder | date=22 December 2007 | location=London | title=London, capital of the world}}</ref> The city is particularly renowned for its theatre quarter, and its [[West End of London|West End]] theatre district has given the name to \"West End theatre\", the strand of mainstream professional theatre staged in the large theatres in London. London is also home to notable cultural attractions such as the [[British Museum]], the [[Tate|Tate Galleries]], the [[National Gallery]], the [[Notting Hill Carnival]] and [[The O2 (London)|The O2]].\n\nThrough music, comedy and theatre, London has a lively nightlife with approximately 25.6 events per thousand people, 44.1% of those events being theatre based.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chadha|first1=Aayush|title=UK Event Data - In Review|url=https://www.tickx.co.uk/article/772|website=www.tickx.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nA variety of landmarks and objects are [[cultural icon]]s associated with London, such as [[Big Ben]], [[Buckingham Palace]] and the [[tube map]]. Many other British cultural icons are strongly associated with London in the minds of visiting tourists, including the [[red telephone box]], the [[AEC Routemaster]] bus, the [[Hackney carriage|black taxi]] and the [[Union Flag]].\n\nThe city is home to many nationalities and the diversity of cultures have shaped the city's culture over time.\n\n==Classical music and opera==\n[[Image:Royal Opera House - Floral Hall - Bow Street - London - 240404.jpg|thumb|left|The Floral Hall of the [[Royal Opera House]]]]\n\nThere are three major concert halls in the capital. One of these is the Barbican Hall at [[Barbican Centre]]; which is home to the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] (LSO) and [[BBC Symphony Orchestra]]. The [[Royal Festival Hall]], based at the [[South Bank|South Bank Centre]] along with the [[Queen Elizabeth Hall]] and the [[Hayward Gallery]] is home to the [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]] (LPO), and the [[Philharmonia]]. The final and largest of all venues is the [[Royal Albert Hall]], which hosts the [[Proms]] each summer. The [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] (RPO) is also based in London at [[Cadogan Hall]].\n\nThere are also several chamber orchestras, some of which specialise in period instrument performances, including the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]], and the [[Academy of St Martin-in-the-Fields|Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields]]. Chamber music venues include the [[Purcell Room]] at the [[South Bank|South Bank Centre]]; the [[Wigmore Hall]] and [[St. John's, Smith Square|St John's, Smith Square]].\n\nA number of [[:Category:London choirs|choirs]] have originated in London, varying in size and musical style. Among the city's large symphonic concert choirs are the [[London Philharmonic Choir]] and [[London Symphony Chorus]], which have their origins as the choral sections of the LPO and the LSO,<ref name=lsc>{{cite web|title=About the LSC|url=http://www.lsc.org.uk/about|publisher=London Symphony Chorus|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=lpo>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.lpc.org.uk/60/history.html|publisher=London Philharmonic Choir|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> the [[London Chorus]], [[London Voices]] and [[the Bach Choir]]. Smaller vocal groups in London include the [[Holst Singers]]<ref>{{cite web|title=About us|url=http://holstsingers.co.uk/about-us/the-choir/|publisher=Holst Singers|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> and the choir of [[the English Concert]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Choir of The English Concert|url=http://www.englishconcert.co.uk/biographies/detail.php?ID=1837|publisher=The English Concert|accessdate=10 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018041745/http://www.englishconcert.co.uk/biographies/detail.php?ID=1837|archivedate=18 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There is also a long tradition of choral singing in Christian churches and cathedrals, and among the choirs associated with [[List of churches in London|London churches]] are the choirs of [[St Paul's Cathedral]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Choir & Musicians|url=http://www.stpauls.co.uk/Worship-Music/Choir-Musicians|publisher=St Paul's Cathedra|accessdate=10 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811111254/http://www.stpauls.co.uk/Worship-Music/Choir-Musicians|archive-date=11 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Choir of Westminster Abbey|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/music/choir|publisher=Westminster Abbey|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> and [[Westminster Cathedral]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Westminster Cathedral Choir|url=http://www.westminstercathedral.org.uk/music_choir.php|publisher=Westminster Cathedral|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> which sing daily services.\n\nThe [[Royal Opera House]] at [[Covent Garden]] is home to the Royal Opera and [[Royal Ballet, London|Royal Ballet]] companies. The other main opera company is the [[English National Opera]]. In the summer opera is performed in a temporary pavilion by [[Opera Holland Park]], and there are occasional performances by visiting opera companies and small freelance professional opera companies.\n\n==Popular music==\n[[File:AmyWinehouseBerlin2007.jpg|thumb|[[Amy Winehouse]] was a singer-songwriter from Southgate, north London.]]\nLondon is famous for its rock scene, and was the starting point of some of the greatest 60s and 70s artists such as [[David Bowie]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[The Clash]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[The Sex Pistols]], [[The Who]], [[Pink Floyd]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and popular 90s acts like [[blur (band)|Blur]] and [[Coldplay]].  Most major bands' tours will pass through London as well, favourite venues being the [[Brixton Academy]], the [[The O2 Arena|O2 Arena]], and the [[Hammersmith Apollo]].\n\nIn addition to spawning the bands mentioned above, London, in its capacity as the UK's cultural centre, has served as the base of a number of internationally important acts, including [[The Beatles]] and [[Elton John]], as well as being instrumental in the birth of [[Electronic dance music|dance music]].\n\nLondon is also known for spawning numerous massively successful pop acts; with the [[Spice Girls]], [[Cliff Richard]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[One Direction]] and [[Little Mix]]   being especially noteworthy.\n\nLondon also has a thriving urban scene, mainly throughout the 21st century. Soul singers like [[Adele]], [[Amy Winehouse]] and [[Lemar]] have found themselves chart, and international success.  [[R&B]] singers such as the [[Sugababes]], [[Leona Lewis]], [[Taio Cruz]], [[Jay Sean]] and [[Alexandra Burke]] are also extremely popular. London also has a strong rap scene; rappers including [[Wiley (rapper)|Wiley]] and [[Dizzee Rascal]] among others have helped contribute to London gaining the status of having the strongest rap scene outside of the USA.\n\nLondon is the home of one of the biggest underground scenes in the world. Genres include [[Uk garage]], [[Drum and bass]], [[Dubstep]], [[2-step garage|2step]] and [[Grime (music)|grime]].\n\n==Festivals==\n[[Image:London - Notting Hill Carnival - Girl in Costume.jpg|thumb|right|Girl in costume at the [[Notting Hill Carnival]]]]\nLondon hosts several festivals, fairs and carnivals throughout the year with over 40 free festivals each year. The most famous is the [[Notting Hill Carnival]], the world's second largest carnival. The carnival takes place over the August bank holiday weekend, and attracts almost 1 million people. It has a distinctly Afro-Caribbean flavour, and highlights include a competition between London's [[steelpan]] bands and a 3-mile street parade with dancing and music.\n\nLondon also hosts the [[Carnaval Del Pueblo]], Europe's greatest Latin American Festival, held on the first Sunday of August each year. Seven countries participate in this street procession, which ends in Burgess Park. Live music, dance, and Funfairs go up to 9:30&nbsp;pm.\n\nThere are also large parades held on [[St. George's Day]] (23 April) and [[St Patrick's Day]] (17 March).  The [[Dance Umbrella]] is held every October, and features a variety of dance companies putting on displays across London.  In addition there are many smaller fairs and parades, including the [[Christmas Without Cruelty Fayre]], a fair held annually to promote [[animal rights]].\n\n[[File:Palace Theatre London.jpg|thumb|left|[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]] at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]]]]\n==Theatre and dance==\nThere are over three dozen major theatres, most concentrated in the [[West End of London|West End]] (see the articles West End theatre and [[List of London venues]]). West End theatres are commercial ventures that host predominantly Musical Theatre shows but genres such as comedy and serious drama are sometimes shown. The subsidised or non-commercial theatre is vibrant in the capital with theatres like the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] and [[Shakespeare's Globe]] both of which are based on the [[South Bank]], the [[Barbican Centre|Barbican]] in the city, the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]] which specialises in new drama, and the [[Old Vic]]; and [[Young Vic]], both in [[Lambeth]]. The [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] which is based in [[Stratford-upon-Avon|Stratford]], presents seasons in London as well. Smaller fringe theatres like [[Battersea Arts Centre]], [[Bloomsbury Theatre]], [[Almeida Theatre]] and [[Tricycle Theatre]] are also popular.\n\nThe capital also boasts a successful dance and physical theatre scene, home to two ballet companies; the [[Royal Ballet]] based at the [[Royal Opera House]] and [[English National Ballet]] based in [[Kensington]], performing at the [[London Coliseum]]. [[Sadler's Wells Theatre]] on Rosebery Avenue in [[Islington]] exclusively shows dance performances throughout the year ranging from existing and new [[Contemporary Dance|Contemporary]] companies, Musical Theatre, and touring ballet companies. Dance performances also take place at the [[Barbican Centre]], [[Peacock Theatre]] (Sadler's Wells), and the [[Queen Elizabeth Hall]]. [[Rambert Dance Company|Rambert]], [[Richard Alston Dance Company]], [[Candoco]], and [[Siobhan Davies Dance]] are all based in London as well as choreographers such as [[Matthew Bourne]], [[Wayne McGregor]], [[Lloyd Newson]], and [[Hofesh Shechter]] also basing their companies within the capital.\n\n==Art==\n[[Image:National Gallery head-on shot.jpg|thumb|[[National Gallery (London)|The National Gallery]] from Trafalgar Square]]\nThe British National collection of Western Art to 1900 is held at [[National Gallery, London|The National Gallery]]. Other major collections of pre-1900 art are The [[Wallace Collection]]; the Courtauld Gallery at the [[Courtauld Institute of Art]]; and [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]]. The national collection of post-1900 art is at [[Tate Modern]] and the national collection of British Art is at [[Tate Britain]]. [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|The National Portrait Gallery]] has a major collection dedicated to prominent British people from all periods. The [[Royal Academy]]'s temporary exhibitions are also important.\n\nIn addition to [[Tate Modern]] major contemporary art venues include [[White Cube]], the [[Saatchi Gallery]], and The [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA]].\n\n==Museums and art galleries==\n\n[[Image:British museum facade (1).jpg|thumb|The main entrance to the [[British Museum]]]]\n{{main|List of London museums}}\n\nLondon is home to over 240 museums,<ref>{{cite web|title=Culture of London|url=http://europe-cities.com/destinations/uk_england/cities/london/culture/|website=Europe-Cities|accessdate=6 July 2015}}</ref> galleries, and other institutions, many of which are free of admission charges and are major [[tourist attraction]]s as well as playing a research role. The first of these to be established was the [[British Museum]] in [[Bloomsbury]], in 1753. Originally containing antiquities, natural history specimens and the national library, the museum now has 7 million artefacts from around the globe. Also of eighteenth-century foundation is the [[Royal Academy|Royal Academy of Arts]]; its [[Royal Academy summer exhibition|summer exhibition]] has been an annual fixture on the London social calendar since 1769. In 1824 the [[National Gallery]] was founded to house the British national collection of Western paintings; this now occupies a prominent position in [[Trafalgar Square]].\n\nIn the latter half of the nineteenth century the locale of [[South Kensington]] was developed as \"[[Albertopolis]]\", a cultural and scientific quarter. Three major national museums are located there: the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] (for the [[applied arts|applied]] and [[Decorative arts]]), the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] and the [[London Science Museum|Science Museum]]. The national gallery of British art is at [[Tate Britain]], originally established as an annexe of the National Gallery in 1897. The Tate Gallery, as it was formerly known, also became a major centre for modern art; in 2000 this collection moved to [[Tate Modern]], a new gallery housed in the former [[Bankside Power Station]]. London's museums of military and maritime history also opened in the twentieth century: the [[Imperial War Museum]] in 1917, and the [[National Maritime Museum]] in 1934.\n\nLondon has several smaller museums of note. The [[Dulwich Picture Gallery]] was the first purpose-built public art gallery in England, opening in 1817. Its architect, Sir [[John Soane]], turned his own house in [[Lincoln's Inn Fields]] into a museum and architectural showcase, known as the [[Sir John Soane's Museum|Soane Museum]]. The [[Wallace Collection]] is a notable small collection of [[Old Master]] paintings and furniture, with an emphasis on French works. The [[Courtauld Institute of Art]], which pioneered the study of [[art history]] in Britain from its foundation in 1932, is now located in [[Somerset House]], the former premises of the Royal Academy. The [[Museum of London]], charting the capital's history, has been located in the [[Barbican Centre|Barbican]] complex since 1976; a [[Museum of London Docklands|sister museum in the Docklands]] opened in 2003.\n\n==Libraries==\n[[File:Maughan-library-1.jpg|thumb|[[Maughan Library]], [[King's College London]]]]\n\nThe [[British Library]], located on [[Euston Road]] in [[St Pancras, London|St Pancras]] is the [[List of largest libraries|largest library in the world]]. It is the [[national library]] of the United Kingdom and is a [[legal deposit library]].<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/british-library|publisher=HM Government|title=British Library|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2003/28/pdfs/ukpga_20030028_en.pdf|publisher=HM Government|website=Legislation|title=Legal Deposit Libraries Act 2003|pages=2-3}}</ref> There are many local public libraries across London, with each borough having its own library system, joined through the London Libraries network.<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.londoncouncils.gov.uk/our-key-themes/culture-sport-and-tourism/arts-and-culture/networks/association-london-chief|title=London Libraries|publisher=London Councils|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref> Some notable local libraries include [[Kensington Central Library]] and the [[Barbican Library]]. There are also private subscription libraries, including the [[London Library]].<ref>{{cite-news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/31732a86-6753-11e9-9adc-98bf1d35a056|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|access-date=3 Jan 2020|date=26 April 2019|title=Shhh! Private libraries are making a quiet comeback}}</ref>\n\nThere are many research libraries in London, including the [[Wellcome Library]] and [[Dana Library and Research Centre|Dana Centre]].<ref>{{cite-news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/futurelondon/culturecity/best-libraries-in-london-wellcome-trust-british-library-canada-water-victoria-and-albert-guildhall-a4072696.html|title=Best libraries in London|publisher=[[Evening Standard]]|access-date=3 January 2020|date=21 Feb 2019}}</ref> There are also many [[academic library|university libraries]], including the [[British Library of Political and Economic Science]] at [[London School of Economics|LSE]], the [[Imperial College Central Library|Central Library]] at [[Imperial College London|Imperial]], the [[Maughan Library]] at [[King's College London|King's]], and the [[Senate House Libraries]] at the [[University of London]]. Many learned institutions host a library such as the [[Inner Temple Library]], and the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]] contains the [[House of Commons Library]] and the [[House of Lords Library]].<ref>{{cite-web|url=https://aim25.com/which_inst.htm|title=List of repositories|access-date=3 Jan 2020|publisher=Archives in London and the M25 area}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/commons-library|title=House of Commons Library|publisher=UK Parliament|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/lords/work-of-the-house-of-lords/lords-library/|title=The House of Lords Library|publisher=UK Parliament|access-date=3 Jan 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Night-life==\n[[Image:BrixtonAcademy.jpg|thumb|[[Brixton Academy]]]]\nApart from the pubs and clubs, there are many music venues. Among the best known are [[Shepherds Bush Empire]], [[Brixton Academy]], [[Hammersmith Apollo]], [[Wembley Arena]], [[The Marquee]], [[The UCL Bloomsbury]], the [[Royal Albert Hall]] and the [[London Astoria]], which has now closed.<ref>http://www.festivalrepublic.com/venues/#Astoria {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220070927/http://www.festivalrepublic.com/venues/ |date=20 December 2007 }}</ref> Between 2007 and 2015, London lost 35% of its grassroots music venues, threatening the city's role as an incubator of new musical talent.<ref>https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/rescue_plan_for_londons_grassroots_music_venues_-_progress_update_-_jan_2017.pdf</ref> London is home to many clubs such as the [[Ministry of Sound]].\n\n\nThere are many other culture related attractions in London, including the [[Avenue of Stars, London|Avenue of Stars]], a walkway similar to the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], with stars commemorating notable individuals or groups.\n\nLondon also has a thriving LGBT community with a high number of venues catering to gays and lesbians, such as [[G-A-Y]], [[The Black Cap]], [[Coleherne public house|The Coleherne]] and [[Heaven (nightclub)|Heaven]]. However, London lost 58% of its [[LGBT]]Q+ night time venues between 2006 and 2017.<ref>https://www.ucl.ac.uk/urbanlab/docs/executive-summary-lgbtq-cultural-infrastructure-in-london-night-venues</ref> Spaces catering to [[Black and Minority Ethnic|BAME]] [[LGBT]]Q+ people have been disproportionately vulnerable to closure.\n\nComedy is widely popular with the capital having around 100 venues showing '[[Alternative Comedy]].' London is also home to [[The Comedy Store (London)|The Comedy Store]] one of the longest running comedy venues in the world.\n\n==Sport==\n{{main|Sport in London}}\n\nLondon is the home of many professional sport teams and has hosted various international sporting events, including the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer Olympics]] in [[1908 Summer Olympics|1908]], [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948]], and [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012]]. [[Association football|Football]] is very popular and London is home to [[Wembley Stadium]] as well as club stadiums such as the [[Emirates Stadium]], [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]. [[Cricket]] grounds such as [[Lord's]] and [[The Oval]] are in London and [[rugby league]] and [[rugby union]] are popular team sports in the city. [[The Boat Race]] and [[The Championships, Wimbledon|The Wimbledon Championships]], among the most famous contests in rowing and tennis, respectively, occur in London. The [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] hosts athletics events.\n\n== Culture Tourism ==\nCultural tourism is growing as London became the second most visited city in the world in 2017,{{cn|date=January 2020}} and many travellers come here to enjoy the British way of living. Culture tourism generates \u00a33.2 billion per year for London's economy and supports around 80,000 jobs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/take_a_closer_look-_a_cultural_tourism_vision_for_london_2015_-_2017.pdf|title=A CULTURAL TOURISM VISION FOR LONDON 2015 \u2013 2017|website=www.london.gov.uk}}</ref> This is the reason why London is now being promoted as a cultural centre to attract more and more tourists and compete with places like Amsterdam, Paris and New York which are known for their authentic culture.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Culture by city in England|London]]\n[[Category:Culture in London| ]]\n", "name_user": "71.221.153.73", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culture_of_London"}
