s_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_total         = 4254\n|pop_est_footnotes        = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_est           = 3178\n|population_density_sq_mi = 2003.83\n|population_density_km2   = 773.77\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Mountain Standard Time|MST]]\n|utc_offset               = -7\n|timezone_DST             = [[Mountain Daylight Time|MDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -6\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 80807 <ref name=ZIPcode>{{cite web|url=http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |title=ZIP Code Lookup |format=[[JavaScript]]/[[HTML]] |publisher=[[United States Postal Service]] |accessdate=September 4, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070903025217/http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |archivedate=September 3, 2007 }}</ref>\n|area_code_type           = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n|area_code                = [[Area code 719|719]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 08-10600\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS feature ID]]\n|blank1_info              = 0204822\n|website                  = [http://www.burlingtoncolo.com/ burlingtoncolo.com]\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Burlington''' is a [[List of cities and towns in Colorado#Home rule municipality|Home Rule Municipality]] and the [[county seat]] of [[Kit Carson County, Colorado|Kit Carson County]], [[Colorado]], United States.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref>  The city population was 4,254 as of the [[2010 United States Census]].<ref name=\"Census2010\"/>\n\n==History==\nBurlington was originally laid out one mile west of its present location in 1887 by a man named Lowell in anticipation of the arrival of the railroad. In addition to having the location wrong, Lowell also did not have title to the land. When the railroad did arrive, the [[Chicago, Rock Island and Pacific Railroad]], it built its depot at the present site of Burlington and those who had built in Old Burlington moved their buildings to the new townsite. Trains began running in 1888. \"The Settlement\", about 12 miles northwest of Burlington, was settled by [[Germans from Russia|German immigrants from Russia]], many from [[Tsebrykove|Hoffnungstal, South Russia]], who, in addition to their homesteads, built Congregational and Lutheran churches.<ref>[http://www.coloradohistoricnewspapers.org/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=Colorado&BaseHref=KCC/1912/12/05&PageLabelPrint=1&EntityId=Ar00100&ViewMode=GIF \"Local and Personal Happenings] notice of a wedding at the Congregational church in the Settlement, page 1 ''Kit Carson County Record'' December 5, 1912</ref><ref>[http://www.bauderhistory.com/pdf/TheBirthoftheGermanSettlement.pdf The Birth of the German Settlement in Kit Carson County], from [http://www.bauderhistory.com/chapter4.html The German Settlement of Kit Carson County, Colorado]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nBurlington is located at {{coord|39|18|15|N|102|16|7|W|type:city}} (39.304293, -102.268683)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> on the [[High Plains (United States)|High Plains]] in eastern Colorado.  According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|2.1|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\nThe easternmost interchange in Colorado on [[Interstate 70 in Colorado|Interstate 70]] is located at Burlington.\n\n===Climate===\nBurlington as a typical High Plains [[semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool semi-arid climate]] with hot, dry summers punctuated by occasional heavy thunderstorm rains, and cold, very dry winters. Snowfall is occasionally heavy \u2013 the 1971 to 2000 mean was {{convert|35.5|in|m|2|disp=or}} \u2013 but mostly the winter weather is very dry and extremely variable in temperatures. More than 33 afternoons (over a third) each winter can be expected to reach or exceed {{convert|50|F|C|disp=or}}, but 6.5 mornings each year will drop to or under {{convert|0|F|C|1}} and 24.6 afternoons do not top freezing.\n<div style=\"width:75%;\">\n{{Weather box\n|location = Burlington, Colorado (1981\u20132010)\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 74\n|Feb record high F = 86\n|Mar record high F = 87\n|Apr record high F = 92\n|May record high F = 101\n|Jun record high F = 107\n|Jul record high F = 105\n|Aug record high F = 103\n|Sep record high F = 100\n|Oct record high F = 93\n|Nov record high F = 81\n|Dec record high F = 76\n|year record high F = 107\n|Jan avg record high F = 66\n|Feb avg record high F = 66\n|Mar avg record high F = 78\n|Apr avg record high F = 85\n|May avg record high F = 94\n|Jun avg record high F = 99\n|Jul avg record high F = 101\n|Aug avg record high F = 98\n|Sep avg record high F = 94\n|Oct avg record high F = 87\n|Nov avg record high F = 76\n|Dec avg record high F = 66\n|year avg record high F = 102\n|Jan high F = 43.6\n|Feb high F = 45.7\n|Mar high F = 54.7\n|Apr high F = 63.5\n|May high F = 74.1\n|Jun high F = 83.6\n|Jul high F = 90.3\n|Aug high F = 86.6\n|Sep high F = 79.2\n|Oct high F = 65.6\n|Nov high F = 53.5\n|Dec high F = 43.2\n|year high F = 65.3\n|Jan low F = 17.0\n|Feb low F = 18.8\n|Mar low F = 25.6\n|Apr low F = 33.8\n|May low F = 44.3\n|Jun low F = 54.2\n|Jul low F = 60.8\n|Aug low F = 58.8\n|Sep low F = 49.3\n|Oct low F = 36.4\n|Nov low F = 25.4\n|Dec low F = 16.5\n|year low F = 36.7\n|Jan avg record low F = &minus;1\n|Feb avg record low F = 3\n|Mar avg record low F = 11\n|Apr avg record low F = 20\n|May avg record low F = 30\n|Jun avg record low F = 42\n|Jul avg record low F = 53\n|Aug avg record low F = 51\n|Sep avg record low F = 36\n|Oct avg record low F = 21\n|Nov avg record low F = 8\n|Dec avg record low F = &minus;3\n|year avg record low F = &minus;7\n|Jan record low F = &minus;12\n|Feb record low F = &minus;11\n|Mar record low F = &minus;3\n|Apr record low F = 16\n|May record low F = 25\n|Jun record low F = 33\n|Jul record low F = 47\n|Aug record low F = 45\n|Sep record low F = 27\n|Oct record low F = 8\n|Nov record low F = &minus;3\n|Dec record low F = &minus;15\n|year record low F = &minus;15\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.14\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.20\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.67\n|Apr precipitation inch = 1.46\n|May precipitation inch = 1.76\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.29\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.38\n|Aug precipitation inch = 2.52\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.06\n|Oct precipitation inch = 1.50\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.28\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.24\n|Jan precipitation days = 2\n|Feb precipitation days = 4\n|Mar precipitation days = 4\n|Apr precipitation days = 8\n|May precipitation days = 9\n|Jun precipitation days = 9\n|Jul precipitation days = 9\n|Aug precipitation days = 11\n|Sep precipitation days = 6\n|Oct precipitation days = 6\n|Nov precipitation days = 3\n|Dec precipitation days = 3\n|year precipitation days = 72\n|unit precipitation days = 0.01 inch\n|source 1 = NOAA<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://www.nws.noaa.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=gld\n  | title = NOWData - NOAA Online Weather Data\n  | publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n  | accessdate = May 5, 2013\n}}</ref>\n|date=May 2013\n}}\n</div>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1890= 146\n|1900= 183\n|1910= 368\n|1920= 991\n|1930= 1280\n|1940= 1280\n|1950= 2247\n|1960= 2090\n|1970= 2828\n|1980= 3107\n|1990= 2941\n|2000= 3678\n|2010= 4254\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=3178\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302111640/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref> of 2010, there were 4,191 people, 1,478 households, and ? families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 1,995.7 people per square mile (776.1/km\u00b2).  There were 1,478 housing units at an average density of 703.8 per square mile (273.7/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 84.3% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 6.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 1.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.5% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 8.5% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.90% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 27.5% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,287 households out of which 32.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.7% were non-families. 30.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.47 and the average family size was 3.11.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.2% under the age of 18, 8.6% from 18 to 24, 32.8% from 25 to 44, 19.7% from 45 to 64, and 13.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 121.6 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 126.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $33,854, and the median income for a family was $42,500. Males had a median income of $29,167 versus $19,018 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $16,054.  About 12.2% of families and 14.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 20.3% of those under age 18 and 15.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Government==\nBurlington is a [[Colorado municipalities#Home rule municipality|Home Rule Municipality]].<ref name=MuniIncCO/>\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:AH-1 on display in front of the VFW Post in Burlington, Colorado.JPG|thumb|right|An [[AH-1 Cobra]] on display outside of the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars|VFW Post]] in Burlington]]\nBurlington Public Schools are part of the [[Burlington Public School District RE-6J]]. The district has one elementary school, one middle school and one high school. Burlington also has several private schools.\n\nBurlington Elementary School, Burlington Middle School and [[Burlington High School (Burlington, Colorado)|Burlington High School]] are located in Burlington.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.greatschools.org/search/search.page?search_type=0&q=burlington&state=CO&c=school|title= Burlington |publisher= GreatSchools, Inc. |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\n===Print===\nBurlington has a weekly [[newspaper]], ''The Burlington Record''.<ref>{{cite web | title = About this Newspaper: The Burlington record | work = Chronicling America | publisher = [[Library of Congress]] | url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn91052057/ | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref> A run of 3 years, 1910\u20131912, of the ''Kit Carson County Record'' is archived in the Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection.<ref>[http://www.coloradohistoricnewspapers.org/Default/Skins/Colorado/Client.asp?Skin=Colorado&AW=1312060892517&AppName=2 Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection]</ref>\n\n===Radio===\nThe following [[radio station]]s are [[city of license|licensed]] to Burlington:\n\n'''AM'''\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" border=\"1\"\n|+ align=bottom |\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Frequency'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''[[Callsign]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=AMQ AM Radio Database Query |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |url=http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/amq.html |accessdate=2009-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825063614/http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/amq.html |archivedate=2009-08-25 }}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Format'''<ref name=Arbitron>{{cite web | title = Station Information Profile | publisher = [[Arbitron]] | url = http://www.arbitron.com/radio_stations/station_information.htm | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Notes'''\n|-\n|1140||[[KNAB (AM)|KNAB]]||[[Adult Standards]]/[[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]]||\n|-\n|}\n\n'''FM'''\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" border=\"1\"\n|+ align=bottom |\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Frequency'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''[[Callsign]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=FMQ FM Radio Database Query |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |url=http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/fmq.html |accessdate=2009-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825071957/http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/fmq.html |archivedate=2009-08-25 }}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Format'''<ref name=Arbitron/>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Notes'''\n|-\n|88.