ite                  = [http://www.burlingtoncolo.com/ burlingtoncolo.com]\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n'''Burlington''' is a [[List of cities and towns in Colorado#Home rule municipality|Home Rule Municipality]] and the [[county seat]] of [[Kit Carson County, Colorado|Kit Carson County]], [[Colorado]], United States.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref>  The city population was 4,254 as of the [[2010 United States Census]].<ref name=\"Census2010\"/>\n\n==History==\nBurlington was originally laid out one mile west of its present location in 1887 by a man named Lowell in anticipation of the arrival of the railroad. In addition to having the location wrong, Lowell also did not have title to the land. When the railroad did arrive, the [[Chicago, Rock Island and Pacific Railroad]], it built its depot at the present site of Burlington and those who had built in Old Burlington moved their buildings to the new townsite. Trains began running in 1888. \"The Settlement\", about 12 miles northwest of Burlington, was settled by [[Germans from Russia|German immigrants from Russia]], many from [[Tsebrykove|Hoffnungstal, South Russia]], who, in addition to their homesteads, built Congregational and Lutheran churches.<ref>[http://www.coloradohistoricnewspapers.org/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=Colorado&BaseHref=KCC/1912/12/05&PageLabelPrint=1&EntityId=Ar00100&ViewMode=GIF \"Local and Personal Happenings] notice of a wedding at the Congregational church in the Settlement, page 1 ''Kit Carson County Record'' December 5, 1912</ref><ref>[http://www.bauderhistory.com/pdf/TheBirthoftheGermanSettlement.pdf The Birth of the German Settlement in Kit Carson County], from [http://www.bauderhistory.com/chapter4.html The German Settlement of Kit Carson County, Colorado]</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nBurlington is located at {{coord|39|18|15|N|102|16|7|W|type:city}} (39.304293, -102.268683)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> on the [[High Plains (United States)|High Plains]] in eastern Colorado.  According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|2.1|sqmi|km2}}, all of it land.\n\nThe easternmost interchange in Colorado on [[Interstate 70 in Colorado|Interstate 70]] is located at Burlington.\n\n===Climate===\nBurlington as a typical High Plains [[semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool semi-arid climate]] with hot, dry summers punctuated by occasional heavy thunderstorm rains, and cold, very dry winters. Snowfall is occasionally heavy \u2013 the 1971 to 2000 mean was {{convert|35.5|in|m|2|disp=or}} \u2013 but mostly the winter weather is very dry and extremely variable in temperatures. More than 33 afternoons (over a third) each winter can be expected to reach or exceed {{convert|50|F|C|disp=or}}, but 6.5 mornings each year will drop to or under {{convert|0|F|C|1}} and 24.6 afternoons do not top freezing.\n<div style=\"width:75%;\">\n{{Weather box\n|location = Burlington, Colorado (1981\u20132010)\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 74\n|Feb record high F = 86\n|Mar record high F = 87\n|Apr record high F = 92\n|May record high F = 101\n|Jun record high F = 107\n|Jul record high F = 105\n|Aug record high F = 103\n|Sep record high F = 100\n|Oct record high F = 93\n|Nov record high F = 81\n|Dec record high F = 76\n|year record high F = 107\n|Jan avg record high F = 66\n|Feb avg record high F = 66\n|Mar avg record high F = 78\n|Apr avg record high F = 85\n|May avg record high F = 94\n|Jun avg record high F = 99\n|Jul avg record high F = 101\n|Aug avg record high F = 98\n|Sep avg record high F = 94\n|Oct avg record high F = 87\n|Nov avg record high F = 76\n|Dec avg record high F = 66\n|year avg record high F = 102\n|Jan high F = 43.6\n|Feb high F = 45.7\n|Mar high F = 54.7\n|Apr high F = 63.5\n|May high F = 74.1\n|Jun high F = 83.6\n|Jul high F = 90.3\n|Aug high F = 86.6\n|Sep high F = 79.2\n|Oct high F = 65.6\n|Nov high F = 53.5\n|Dec high F = 43.2\n|year high F = 65.3\n|Jan low F = 17.0\n|Feb low F = 18.8\n|Mar low F = 25.6\n|Apr low F = 33.8\n|May low F = 44.3\n|Jun low F = 54.2\n|Jul low F = 60.8\n|Aug low F = 58.8\n|Sep low F = 49.3\n|Oct low F = 36.4\n|Nov low F = 25.4\n|Dec low F = 16.5\n|year low F = 36.7\n|Jan avg record low F = &minus;1\n|Feb avg record low F = 3\n|Mar avg record low F = 11\n|Apr avg record low F = 20\n|May avg record low F = 30\n|Jun avg record low F = 42\n|Jul avg record low F = 53\n|Aug avg record low F = 51\n|Sep avg record low F = 36\n|Oct avg record low F = 21\n|Nov avg record low F = 8\n|Dec avg record low F = &minus;3\n|year avg record low F = &minus;7\n|Jan record low F = &minus;12\n|Feb record low F = &minus;11\n|Mar record low F = &minus;3\n|Apr record low F = 16\n|May record low F = 25\n|Jun record low F = 33\n|Jul record low F = 47\n|Aug record low F = 45\n|Sep record low F = 27\n|Oct record low F = 8\n|Nov record low F = &minus;3\n|Dec record low F = &minus;15\n|year record low F = &minus;15\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.14\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.20\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.67\n|Apr precipitation inch = 1.46\n|May precipitation inch = 1.76\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.29\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.38\n|Aug precipitation inch = 2.52\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.06\n|Oct precipitation inch = 1.50\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.28\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.24\n|Jan precipitation days = 2\n|Feb precipitation days = 4\n|Mar precipitation days = 4\n|Apr precipitation days = 8\n|May precipitation days = 9\n|Jun precipitation days = 9\n|Jul precipitation days = 9\n|Aug precipitation days = 11\n|Sep precipitation days = 6\n|Oct precipitation days = 6\n|Nov precipitation days = 3\n|Dec precipitation days = 3\n|year precipitation days = 72\n|unit precipitation days = 0.01 inch\n|source 1 = NOAA<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://www.nws.noaa.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=gld\n  | title = NOWData - NOAA Online Weather Data\n  | publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]\n  | accessdate = May 5, 2013\n}}</ref>\n|date=May 2013\n}}\n</div>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1890= 146\n|1900= 183\n|1910= 368\n|1920= 991\n|1930= 1280\n|1940= 1280\n|1950= 2247\n|1960= 2090\n|1970= 2828\n|1980= 3107\n|1990= 2941\n|2000= 3678\n|2010= 4254\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=3178\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302111640/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=March 2, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref> of 2010, there were 4,191 people, 1,478 households, and ? families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 1,995.7 people per square mile (776.1/km\u00b2).  There were 1,478 housing units at an average density of 703.8 per square mile (273.7/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 84.3% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 6.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 1.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.5% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 8.5% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.90% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 27.5% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,287 households out of which 32.9% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.7% were non-families. 30.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.47 and the average family size was 3.11.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 25.2% under the age of 18, 8.6% from 18 to 24, 32.8% from 25 to 44, 19.7% from 45 to 64, and 13.7% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 121.6 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 126.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $33,854, and the median income for a family was $42,500. Males had a median income of $29,167 versus $19,018 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $16,054.  About 12.2% of families and 14.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 20.3% of those under age 18 and 15.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Government==\nBurlington is a [[Colorado municipalities#Home rule municipality|Home Rule Municipality]].<ref name=MuniIncCO/>\n\n==Education==\n[[Image:AH-1 on display in front of the VFW Post in Burlington, Colorado.JPG|thumb|right|An [[AH-1 Cobra]] on display outside of the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars|VFW Post]] in Burlington]]\nBurlington Public Schools are part of the [[Burlington Public School District RE-6J]]. The district has one elementary school, one middle school and one high school. Burlington also has several private schools.\n\nBurlington Elementary School, Burlington Middle School and [[Burlington High School (Burlington, Colorado)|Burlington High School]] are located in Burlington.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.greatschools.org/search/search.page?search_type=0&q=burlington&state=CO&c=school|title= Burlington |publisher= GreatSchools, Inc. |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\n===Print===\nBurlington has a weekly [[newspaper]], ''The Burlington Record''.<ref>{{cite web | title = About this Newspaper: The Burlington record | work = Chronicling America | publisher = [[Library of Congress]] | url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn91052057/ | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref> A run of 3 years, 1910-1912, of the ''Kit Carson County Record'' is archived in the Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection.<ref>[http://www.coloradohistoricnewspapers.org/Default/Skins/Colorado/Client.asp?Skin=Colorado&AW=1312060892517&AppName=2 Colorado Historic Newspapers Collection]</ref>\n\n===Radio===\nThe following [[radio station]]s are [[city of license|licensed]] to Burlington:\n\n'''AM'''\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" border=\"1\"\n|+ align=bottom |\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Frequency'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''[[Callsign]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=AMQ AM Radio Database Query |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |url=http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/amq.html |accessdate=2009-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825063614/http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/amq.html |archivedate=2009-08-25 }}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Format'''<ref name=Arbitron>{{cite web | title = Station Information Profile | publisher = [[Arbitron]] | url = http://www.arbitron.com/radio_stations/station_information.htm | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Notes'''\n|-\n|1140||[[KNAB (AM)|KNAB]]||[[Adult Standards]]/[[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]]||\n|-\n|}\n\n'''FM'''\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" border=\"1\"\n|+ align=bottom |\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Frequency'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''[[Callsign]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=FMQ FM Radio Database Query |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |url=http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/fmq.html |accessdate=2009-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090825071957/http://www.fcc.gov/mb/audio/fmq.html |archivedate=2009-08-25 }}</ref>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Format'''<ref name=Arbitron/>\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Notes'''\n|-\n|88.1||[[CSN International|K201FK]]||[[Christian radio|Christian]]||Translator of [[KAWZ]], [[Twin Falls, Idaho]]\n|-\n|89.5||[[KTLF|K208CH]]||[[Contemporary Christian]]||Translator of [[KTLF]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]]\n|-\n|104.1||[[KNAB-FM]]||[[Country music|Country]]||\n|-\n|}\n\n==National Historic Landmark==\n*[[Elitch Gardens Carousel|Kit Carson County Carousel]] (National Historic Landmark)\n\n==Notable people==\nNotable individuals who were born in or have lived in Burlington include:\n* [[Mark Hillman]] (1967- ), Colorado state legislator<ref>{{cite web | title = Centennial Institute - Staff & Fellows | publisher = Colorado Christian University | url = http://www.ccu.edu/centennial/staff-and-fellows/ | accessdate = 2016-06-21}}</ref>\n* [[Robert P. Kerr]] (1892-1960), film director, actor, screenwriter<ref>{{cite web | title = Robert P. Kerr | publisher = IMDb | url = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0449789/ | accessdate = 2016-06-21}}</ref>\n* [[John M. Lounge|Mike Lounge]] (1946-2011), engineer, astronaut<ref>{{cite web | title = Biographical Data - John M. \"Mike\" Lounge | publisher = NASA | url = http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/lounge-jm.html | accessdate = 2016-06-21 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110405230008/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/lounge-jm.html | archive-date = 2011-04-05 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n* [[Beau McCoy]] (1980- ), [[Nebraska]] state legislator<ref>{{cite web | title = Beau McCoy's Biography | publisher = Vote Smart | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/103139/beau-mccoy#.V2mnzPkrKXI | accessdate = 2016-06-21}}</ref>\n* [[Susan Phillips (politician)|Susan Phillips]] (1949- ), [[Missouri]] state legislator<ref>{{cite web | title = Susan Phillips' Biography | publisher = Vote Smart | url = http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/20542/susan-phillips#.V2mm2fkrKXI | accessdate = 2016-06-21}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|North America|<!--Northern America-->|United States|Colorado}}\n*[[Philadelphia Toboggan Company Carousel 12]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.burlingtoncolo.com/ City of Burlington]\n*[http://dtdapps.coloradodot.info/staticdata/Downloads/CityMaps/BURLINGTON.pdf Map of Burlington], CDOT\n*[http://www.bauderhistory.com/pdf/TheEarlyDaysofBurlington.pdf The Early Days of Burlington (PDF)]\n\n{{Kit Carson County, Colorado}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Kit Carson County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Cities in Colorado]]\n[[Category:County seats in Colorado]]\n[[Category:German-Russian culture in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1887]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrint:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1910-1912 \u2192 1910\u20131912", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burlington,_Colorado"}
{"title_page": "Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)\n| cover      = Brandy_-_Looking_Glass.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Looking Glass (band)|Looking Glass]]\n| album      = [[Looking Glass (Looking Glass album)|Looking Glass]]\n| B-side     = One by One\n| released   = May 18, 1972\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 1972\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/brandy-youre-a-fine-girl-sony-mw0000050550 |title=Brandy (You're a Fine Girl) [Sony&#93; - Looking Glass &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=1998-04-28 |accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:55 <small>(Single remix/edit)</small><br />3:10 <small>(Album mix version)</small>\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Elliot Lurie]]\n| producer   = Mike Gershman, Bob Liftin and the Looking Glass\n| prev_title = Golden Rainbow\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Jimmy Loves Mary-Anne]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n\n\"'''Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)'''\" is a 1972 song by the American pop rock band [[Looking Glass (band)|Looking Glass]], from their debut album ''[[Looking Glass (Looking Glass album)|Looking Glass]]''. It was written by Looking Glass lead guitarist and co-vocalist [[Elliot Lurie]]. The song was originally released as a [[B-side]] to the single \"Don't It Make You Feel Good\", but was then released as a single itself due to unexpectedly high demand (with \"One By One\" as its B-side).\n\nThe single reached number one on both the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and [[Cash Box Top 100|''Cash Box'' Top 100]] charts, remaining in the top position for one week. It reached number two on the former chart for four weeks, stuck behind [[Gilbert O'Sullivan]]'s smash hit \"[[Alone Again (Naturally)]]\", before reaching number one, only to be dethroned by \"Alone Again (Naturally)\" the week after. [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] ranked it as the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1972|12th song of 1972]].\n\n==Meaning==\nThe lyrics tell of Brandy, a [[barmaid]] in a busy [[seaport]] harbor town which serves \"a hundred ships a day.\" Though lonely sailors flirt with her, she pines for one who has long since left her because he claimed his life, his love, and his lady, was \u201cthe sea.\u201d\n\nThe urban myth that Brandy was based on [[Mary Ellis grave|Mary Ellis]] (1750\u20131828), a spinster in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey|New Brunswick]], [[New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Mary Ellis Grave |url= http://www.weirdnj.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=49&Itemid=28 |publisher=weirdnj.com |accessdate= April 15, 2012}}</ref> has been refuted by Lurie himself.<ref>{{cite web |title= The urban legends of 'Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)' |url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/story-behind-the-song/2016/12/16/urban-legends-brandy-youre-fine-girl/95397738/ |publisher= tennessean.com}}</ref>\n\nLurie also refutes<ref>{{Citation|last=The Tennessean|title=Story Behind the Song: 'Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)'|date=2016-12-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqzC5kUYrpg|accessdate=2017-08-24}}</ref> the suggestion that the song was written by songwriter Stephen Homner, and eventually sold to Elliot Lurie after Lurie expressed interest in the song.\n\n==Release==\nIn February 1972, Robert Mandel was the Epic Records Promotion Manager in [[Washington, D.C.]] He received a test pressing of an album by Looking Glass, then a new group. He took the test pressing around to every radio station in the Washington/Baltimore region. At the time, [[WPGC-FM|WPGC AM/FM]] was one of the leading Top 40 stations in the country and was the number one radio station in DC. Harv Moore was the Program Director. He put the song into a one-hour rotation for two days and as Moore related at the time, \"the switchboard lit up like a Christmas tree\". He said that he had never received a response like that on a record in his 15 years in radio. Based on the airplay at WPGC and all the other Top 40 stations that followed, Epic rush-released the single of \"Brandy\". Based on requests alone, two weeks later, when the single finally hit the stores, \"Brandy\" was the number one record in DC without a single copy yet sold. Other stations around the country started playing it and it ended up being a number one million seller.  A year later when Moore celebrated his 10th Anniversary at WPGC, Looking Glass returned the favor and played at the bash the station held in his honor.\n\n==Influence==\nFollowing the song's release in 1972, \"Brandy\" increased in popularity as a girl's name in the United States. According to data from the [[Social Security Administration]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Popular Baby Names |url=http://www.ssa.gov/cgi-bin/babyname.cgi |publisher=Ssa.gov |date=August 26, 2009 |accessdate=April 15, 2012}}</ref> Brandy was the 353rd most popular name in 1971, 140th in 1972, and, in 1973 (the first full year after the song's popularity), 82nd.\n\n[[Barry Manilow]]'s 1974 \"[[Mandy (Barry Manilow song)|Mandy]]\" was a cover of a song originally titled \"Brandy\", released in February 1972 by [[Scott English]]; however, Manilow changed the title following the success of the Looking Glass single, so as not to get the two songs confused.<ref>{{cite web |last=Huey |first=Steve |title=Mandy |url={{Allmusic |class=song |id=t1341700 |pure_url=yes}} |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=June 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Stanley]] of the rock band [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] wrote that \"Brandy\" helped inspire the band's 1976 hit \"[[Hard Luck Woman]]\" in his 2014 memoir ''Face the Music: A Life Exposed.''{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nThe 2005 song \"Same Old 45\" by [[Sarah Borges]], from the album ''Silver City'', retells the story of Brandy from her point of view.\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{In popular culture|date=November 2018}}\n* This song was used in the films ''[[Lords of Dogtown]],'' ''[[Say Anything...]],'' ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]],'' ''[[A Very Brady Sequel]]'', ''[[Lymelife]]'', and the 2018 Spike Lee film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]].'' It was also used in an episode of the 2009 television show ''[[Harper's Island]]'', and it can be heard in the background in a scene set in the longshoremen's bar in Season 2 of ''[[The Wire]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Alvarez |first=Rafael |title=The Wire:Truth Be Told |publisher=Pocket Books |date=2004 |page=240 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ozwbjrf3thIC&pg=RA1-PA56}}</ref> A [[Beautiful Music]] instrumental version can be heard in the background when Chris Knight is touring his potential future employer in the film ''[[Real Genius]]''.\n* Fantasy author [[Alex Bledsoe]] used Brandy's name and the song's story for his novel ''Wake of the Bloody Angel''.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n* In ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Principal Charming]]\", [[Selma Bouvier|Selma]] sings the song (using a slower, mournful tempo and tone) to [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] as she is putting her to bed. In TV series companion book ''[[The Simpsons Uncensored Family Album]]'', [[Marge Simpson|Marge]] wrote that her paternal grandmother once told her that the song \"Brandy\" was based on Marge's paternal grandfather's life.\n* The song is included on the soundtrack of ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]]''. It appears in the opening scene<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hiatt|first1=Brian|title=Inside the 'Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2' Soundtrack|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-the-guardians-of-the-galaxy-vol-2-soundtrack-w477515|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref> and again in a scene on [[Ego the Living Planet]], when Ego uses the lyrics as metaphor to explain his experience as a cosmos-wandering [[Celestial (comics)|Celestial]] who fell in love with [[Star-Lord|Peter Quill]]'s mother on Earth. Ego called the song \"one of Earth's greatest musical compositions, perhaps the greatest.\"\n*Doug Heffernan ([[Kevin James]]) sings the song at a karaoke bar in the episode \"G'night Stalker\" on the TV program ''[[The King of Queens]]''.\n*The song appears in a 2019 [[TV commercial]] for the [[Ford F150]] pickup truck.\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Ray Conniff]] and His Singers covered the song on the 1972 album ''Alone Again (Naturally)''.\n* [[Washboard Jungle]] often performs this song as an encore, and recorded it on their 1994 album ''[[The Wash Cycle]]''.  They play it considerably faster than the original.\n* [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] performed a cover version of the song on their ''[[Red Hot Chili Peppers Live in Hyde Park]]'' album and during their 2004 tour. They again performed it in May 2017 for the first time in twelve years.\n* [[Kenny Chesney]] performed a cover version for the Target Bonus Tracks on his 2005 album ''[[The Road and the Radio]]''.\n* [[Gonzalez (band)|Gonzalez]] performed a cover of this song released as a single on the EMI label. ''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Gonzalez-Brandy-Youre-A-Fine-Girl-White-Lightning/master/604630 |title=Gonzalez - Brandy (You're A Fine Girl) / White Lightning |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>''\n* [[Raymond Coats]] (West Coast Groove Band) performs a cover to be released as a single through CDBaby in February 2020.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Elliot Lurie]]\u2014Guitars, vocals\n*Larry Gonsky\u2014Keyboards, vocals\n*Peter Sweval\u2014Bass, vocals, cowbell \n*Jeff Grob\u2014Drum kit\n*[[Larry Fallon]]\u2014Horns arrangements\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1972)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |title=Forum - 1970 (ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts) |website=Australian-charts.com |accessdate=2016-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602084720/http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |archivedate=June 2, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4202&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=6f06s7icu164cmvecg8iitjbi0 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |accessdate=2016-10-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022231507/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4202&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=6f06s7icu164cmvecg8iitjbi0 |archive-date=October 22, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand (''Listener'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search+listener&qsongid=3775#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - search listener|website=www.flavourofnz.co.nz}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|South Africa<ref>http://www.rock.co.za/files/sa_charts_1969_1989_songs_(A-B).html</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|UK\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|51\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Easy Listening]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Joel |last= Whitburn |authorlink= Joel Whitburn |year= 1993 |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961\u20131993 |publisher= Record Research |page=143}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]''<ref>http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/19720902.html</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1972)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|75\n|-\n|Canada\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/1972YESP.html# |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 27, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814104924/http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/1972YESP.html# |archive-date=August 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|looking-glass|brandy-youre-a-fine-girl}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandy (You're A Fine Girl)}}\n[[Category:1972 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:American soft rock songs]]\n[[Category:1972 songs]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Looking Glass (band) songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)\n| cover      = Brandy_-_Looking_Glass.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Looking Glass (band)|Looking Glass]]\n| album      = [[Looking Glass (Looking Glass album)|Looking Glass]]\n| B-side     = One by One\n| released   = May 18, 1972\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 1972\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/brandy-youre-a-fine-girl-sony-mw0000050550 |title=Brandy (You're a Fine Girl) [Sony&#93; - Looking Glass &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=1998-04-28 |accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref>\n| length     = 2:55 <small>(Single remix/edit)</small><br />3:10 <small>(Album mix version)</small>\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Elliot Lurie]]\n| producer   = Mike Gershman, Bob Liftin and the Looking Glass\n| prev_title = Golden Rainbow\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Jimmy Loves Mary-Anne]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n\n\"'''Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)'''\" is a 1972 song by the American pop rock band [[Looking Glass (band)|Looking Glass]], from their debut album ''[[Looking Glass (Looking Glass album)|Looking Glass]]''. It was written by Looking Glass lead guitarist and co-vocalist [[Elliot Lurie]]. The song was originally released as a [[B-side]] to the single \"Don't It Make You Feel Good\", but was then released as a single itself due to unexpectedly high demand (with \"One By One\" as its B-side).\n\nThe single reached number one on both the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and [[Cash Box Top 100|''Cash Box'' Top 100]] charts, remaining in the top position for one week. It reached number two on the former chart for four weeks, stuck behind [[Gilbert O'Sullivan]]'s \"[[Alone Again (Naturally)]]\", before reaching number one, only to be dethroned by \"Alone Again (Naturally)\" the week after. [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] ranked it as the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1972|12th song of 1972]].\n\n==Meaning==\nThe lyrics tell of Brandy, a [[barmaid]] in a busy [[seaport]] harbor town which serves \"a hundred ships a day.\" Though lonely sailors flirt with her, she pines for one who has long since left her because he claimed his life, his love, and his lady, was \u201cthe sea.\u201d\n\nThe urban myth that Brandy was based on [[Mary Ellis grave|Mary Ellis]] (1750\u20131828), a spinster in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey|New Brunswick]], [[New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Mary Ellis Grave |url= http://www.weirdnj.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=49&Itemid=28 |publisher=weirdnj.com |accessdate= April 15, 2012}}</ref> has been refuted by Lurie himself.<ref>{{cite web |title= The urban legends of 'Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)' |url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/story-behind-the-song/2016/12/16/urban-legends-brandy-youre-fine-girl/95397738/ |publisher= tennessean.com}}</ref>\n\nLurie also refutes<ref>{{Citation|last=The Tennessean|title=Story Behind the Song: 'Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)'|date=2016-12-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqzC5kUYrpg|accessdate=2017-08-24}}</ref> the suggestion that the song was written by songwriter Stephen Homner, and eventually sold to Elliot Lurie after Lurie expressed interest in the song.\n\n==Release==\nIn February 1972, Robert Mandel was the Epic Records Promotion Manager in [[Washington, D.C.]] He received a test pressing of an album by Looking Glass, then a new group. He took the test pressing around to every radio station in the Washington/Baltimore region. At the time, [[WPGC-FM|WPGC AM/FM]] was one of the leading Top 40 stations in the country and was the number one radio station in DC. Harv Moore was the Program Director. He put the song into a one-hour rotation for two days and as Moore related at the time, \"the switchboard lit up like a Christmas tree\". He said that he had never received a response like that on a record in his 15 years in radio. Based on the airplay at WPGC and all the other Top 40 stations that followed, Epic rush-released the single of \"Brandy\". Based on requests alone, two weeks later, when the single finally hit the stores, \"Brandy\" was the number one record in DC without a single copy yet sold. Other stations around the country started playing it and it ended up being a number one million seller.  A year later when Moore celebrated his 10th Anniversary at WPGC, Looking Glass returned the favor and played at the bash the station held in his honor.\n\n==Influence==\nFollowing the song's release in 1972, \"Brandy\" increased in popularity as a girl's name in the United States. According to data from the [[Social Security Administration]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Popular Baby Names |url=http://www.ssa.gov/cgi-bin/babyname.cgi |publisher=Ssa.gov |date=August 26, 2009 |accessdate=April 15, 2012}}</ref> Brandy was the 353rd most popular name in 1971, 140th in 1972, and, in 1973 (the first full year after the song's popularity), 82nd.\n\n[[Barry Manilow]]'s 1974 \"[[Mandy (Barry Manilow song)|Mandy]]\" was a cover of a song originally titled \"Brandy\", released in February 1972 by [[Scott English]]; however, Manilow changed the title following the success of the Looking Glass single, so as not to get the two songs confused.<ref>{{cite web |last=Huey |first=Steve |title=Mandy |url={{Allmusic |class=song |id=t1341700 |pure_url=yes}} |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=June 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Stanley]] of the rock band [[Kiss (band)|KISS]] wrote that \"Brandy\" helped inspire the band's 1976 hit \"[[Hard Luck Woman]]\" in his 2014 memoir ''Face the Music: A Life Exposed.''{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n\nThe 2005 song \"Same Old 45\" by [[Sarah Borges]], from the album ''Silver City'', retells the story of Brandy from her point of view.\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{In popular culture|date=November 2018}}\n* This song was used in the films ''[[Lords of Dogtown]],'' ''[[Say Anything...]],'' ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]],'' ''[[A Very Brady Sequel]]'', ''[[Lymelife]]'', and the 2018 Spike Lee film ''[[BlacKkKlansman]].'' It was also used in an episode of the 2009 television show ''[[Harper's Island]]'', and it can be heard in the background in a scene set in the longshoremen's bar in Season 2 of ''[[The Wire]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Alvarez |first=Rafael |title=The Wire:Truth Be Told |publisher=Pocket Books |date=2004 |page=240 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ozwbjrf3thIC&pg=RA1-PA56}}</ref> A [[Beautiful Music]] instrumental version can be heard in the background when Chris Knight is touring his potential future employer in the film ''[[Real Genius]]''.\n* Fantasy author [[Alex Bledsoe]] used Brandy's name and the song's story for his novel ''Wake of the Bloody Angel''.{{cn|date=November 2018}}\n* In ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Principal Charming]]\", [[Selma Bouvier|Selma]] sings the song (using a slower, mournful tempo and tone) to [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] as she is putting her to bed. In TV series companion book ''[[The Simpsons Uncensored Family Album]]'', [[Marge Simpson|Marge]] wrote that her paternal grandmother once told her that the song \"Brandy\" was based on Marge's paternal grandfather's life.\n* The song is included on the soundtrack of ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]]''. It appears in the opening scene<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hiatt|first1=Brian|title=Inside the 'Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2' Soundtrack|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/inside-the-guardians-of-the-galaxy-vol-2-soundtrack-w477515|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref> and again in a scene on [[Ego the Living Planet]], when Ego uses the lyrics as metaphor to explain his experience as a cosmos-wandering [[Celestial (comics)|Celestial]] who fell in love with [[Star-Lord|Peter Quill]]'s mother on Earth. Ego called the song \"one of Earth's greatest musical compositions, perhaps the greatest.\"\n*Doug Heffernan ([[Kevin James]]) sings the song at a karaoke bar in the episode \"G'night Stalker\" on the TV program ''[[The King of Queens]]''.\n*The song appears in a 2019 [[TV commercial]] for the [[Ford F150]] pickup truck.\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Ray Conniff]] and His Singers covered the song on the 1972 album ''Alone Again (Naturally)''.\n* [[Washboard Jungle]] often performs this song as an encore, and recorded it on their 1994 album ''[[The Wash Cycle]]''.  They play it considerably faster than the original.\n* [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] performed a cover version of the song on their ''[[Red Hot Chili Peppers Live in Hyde Park]]'' album and during their 2004 tour. They again performed it in May 2017 for the first time in twelve years.\n* [[Kenny Chesney]] performed a cover version for the Target Bonus Tracks on his 2005 album ''[[The Road and the Radio]]''.\n* [[Gonzalez (band)|Gonzalez]] performed a cover of this song released as a single on the EMI label. ''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Gonzalez-Brandy-Youre-A-Fine-Girl-White-Lightning/master/604630 |title=Gonzalez - Brandy (You're A Fine Girl) / White Lightning |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>''\n* [[Raymond Coats]] (West Coast Groove Band) performs a cover to be released as a single through CDBaby in February 2020.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Elliot Lurie]]\u2014Guitars, vocals\n*Larry Gonsky\u2014Keyboards, vocals\n*Peter Sweval\u2014Bass, vocals, cowbell \n*Jeff Grob\u2014Drum kit\n*[[Larry Fallon]]\u2014Horns arrangements\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1972)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |title=Forum - 1970 (ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts) |website=Australian-charts.com |accessdate=2016-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602084720/http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=35092 |archivedate=June 2, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4202&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=6f06s7icu164cmvecg8iitjbi0 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |accessdate=2016-10-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022231507/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4202&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=6f06s7icu164cmvecg8iitjbi0 |archive-date=October 22, 2014 |u